# Pre-Commit Reviewer Checklist

**Automated checks** (ruff, mypy, tsc, eslint, detect-private-key) run via
`.pre-commit-config.yaml` on every `git commit`. This checklist covers only what
those tools cannot detect.

---

## Architecture Layer Boundaries

- [ ] `api/routes/` are thin — **parse input → call one use case → return DTO**. No conditional
      business logic, no branching on domain state, no direct DB or HTTP calls inside routes.
- [ ] Nothing in `domain/` or `application/` imports from `infrastructure/`, `fastapi`,
      `sqlalchemy`, `httpx`, `redis`, or any third-party library.
- [ ] All GitHub API calls go through `infrastructure/github/` only.
- [ ] All Gemini calls go through `infrastructure/ai/gemini_client.py` only — agent files
      must not import `google.generativeai` directly.
- [ ] All queue operations go through `infrastructure/queue/upstash_redis_client.py` only.

---

## Security (not caught by detect-private-key)

- [ ] `X-Hub-Signature-256` HMAC is validated **before** any webhook payload is processed.
      The validation is not behind a feature flag or try/except that swallows failures.
- [ ] Every non-public route (`/repos`, `/reviews`, `/jobs`) calls `auth_middleware` or
      `Depends(get_current_user)`. Check added routes specifically — no accidentally public endpoints.
- [ ] Columns ending `_encrypted` in DB writes are AES-256 encrypted before insert. Raw tokens
      are never passed to the repository layer.
- [ ] No secrets in comments, log messages, or exception strings (detect-private-key catches
      key patterns but not e.g. `# token was: <value>` comments).

---

## Agent / LangGraph

- [ ] Agent node functions are **pure state transformers** — they receive `ReviewState` and
      return `ReviewState`. No DB writes, no HTTP calls, no Redis pushes inside agent logic.
      Side effects belong in the use case layer that wraps the graph run.
- [ ] All Gemini calls use structured output (Pydantic schema). No `json.loads(response.text)`.
- [ ] New agent node has `@trace_agent` decorator. No unwrapped agent functions.
- [ ] `ReviewState` is the only shared data structure in the graph — no module-level caches,
      no class-level state on agent nodes.

---

## Data / Database

- [ ] No destructive migration in a single step. `DROP COLUMN` requires a prior deprecation
      migration. `ALTER COLUMN` changing type requires a backfill step first.
- [ ] `UNIQUE(repository_id, head_sha)` on `review_jobs` is not bypassed — no raw INSERT
      that skips the conflict check.
- [ ] `pull_request.closed` webhook handler enqueues the embedding cleanup job. If you added
      a new review trigger path, confirm cleanup is also wired.

---

## Concurrency & Reliability

See `architecture.mdc` § Concurrency & Reliability.

- [ ] Webhook path only enqueues — no pipeline/diff/agent work in the request handler
- [ ] Duplicate PR events for the same `head_sha` do not create a second job
- [ ] Worker acks Redis messages only after successful dispatch
- [ ] Persist + GitHub post steps are safe to replay (idempotent guards)

---

## Process

- [ ] New external Python or npm dependency added? → recorded in `decisions.mdc` with
      context and alternatives considered.
- [ ] New API endpoint added? → `schema.mdc` API contract table updated.
- [ ] Changed a locked decision (model, hosting, queue, auth)? → flagged in `decisions.mdc`
      with the reason for change.

---

## Test Coverage (not caught by automated tools)

- [ ] New use case → unit test with mocked domain interfaces (no real DB, Gemini, or Redis).
- [ ] New API route → integration test: happy path (2xx) + missing auth (401) + bad ID (404).
- [ ] New agent node → unit test with a sample diff fixture from `tests/fixtures/`.
- [ ] New `pull_request` event handler → test that the correct job type is enqueued.

---

## How to Invoke Manual Review

```
/review-bugbot    — full Bugbot review of branch changes vs main
/review-security  — security-focused review of branch changes
```
